commitResults.messageTitle: renamed chatbot and added greet and exit functionalities
Added the ability to store whatever text entered by the user and display them back to the user when requested.
Added the ability to mark tasks as done and added the ability to change the status back to not done.
Added todo, deadline and event tasks
Used the input/output redirection technique to semi-automate the testing of Duke.
Taught the chatbot to deal with errors such as incorrect inputs entered by the user.
Added support for deleting tasks from the list.
Add feature to save and load tasks in a hard disk
commitResults.messageBody:
TaskList reloads when chatbot restarts.

This prevents users from keeping track of their task history.

Saving the tasks in a hard disk automatically whenever the task list
changes and loading the data from the hard disk when the chatbot starts
up allows users to better keep track of their task history.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add feature to teach Chatbot to understand dates and times
commitResults.messageBody:
User can input any type of dates and times. This makes the format
unstandardised and messy.

Teaching the Chatbot how to understand dates and times makes task list
neater and easier to read.

commitResults.messageTitle: Edit code to follow OOP principles
commitResults.messageBody:
There are some parts of the code that violate OOP principles.

Adding additional classes such as Ui and Parser can improve the code
quality.

All classes are under the same directory.

Organising the classes into packages allows for easier management

Need to use manual testing to test for bugs in the code. Adding JUnit
tests help to make testing more efficient.
